[anchor=clickme][u][b]I. What is Data Encapsulation[/b][/u][/anchor]

Alright, this is kind of hard to explain. Data encapsulation, often reffered too as a [i]wrapper[/i] or [i]container[/i], is pretty much a way to [i]encapsulate[/i] your data. It's pretty much packaging all of your seperated data into one [i]Object[/i]. Data encapsulation is one of the four fundamental OOP concepts, and its ironic because data encapsulation was the first thing that I learned about Object Orientation. In chapter three I'm going to show you specific examples in winterLove where data encapsulation could be (should be...) utilized. 




[anchor=clickme2][u][b]II. Why you're better off using Data Encapsulation[/b][/u][/anchor]

[ul][li]Maintainability[/li]
[li]The fields of a class can be made read-only or write-only[/li]
[li]A class can have total control over what is stored in its fields[/li]
[li]Flexibility[/li]
[li]Store data in a more manageable way[/li]
[li]The users of a class do not know how the class stores its data. A class can change the data type of a field, and users of the class do not need to change any of their code.[/li][/ul]





[anchor=clickme3][u][b]III. Examples of how Data Encapsulation can be Utilized[/b][/u][/anchor]

[u]Example one, global items:[/u]

[code=java]public static int[] globalItemAmount = new int[15001];
public static int[] globalItemController = new int[15001];
public static int[] globalItemID = new int[15001];
public static boolean[] globalItemStatic = new boolean[15001];
public static int[] globalItemTicks = new int[15001];
public static int[] globalItemX = new int[15001];
public static int[] globalItemY = new int[15001];[/code]

[code=java]globalItemController[i] = itemController;
globalItemID[i] = itemID;
globalItemX[i] = itemX;
globalItemY[i] = itemY;
globalItemAmount[i] = itemAmount;
globalItemStatic[i] = itemStatic;
globalItemTicks[i] = 0;[/code]


Seriously? That looks pretty redundant to me. Now, this is what we can do if we make a [i]container[/i] class.


[code=java]public static GlobalItem[] globalItems = new GlobalItem[15001];[/code]

[code=java]globalItems[i].setItemOwner(itemController);
globalItems[i].setID(itemID);
globalItems[i].setPosition(position);
globalItems[i].setAmount(itemAmount);
globalItems[i].setStatic(itemStatic);
globalItems[i].setTicks(0);[/code]

A lot better... wouldn't you agree? Don't you think the object orientated way looks more... [b]maintainable[/b]? We can edit a bunch of different values with [b]one[/b] field!



[u]Example two, player positions:[/u]

[code=java]public int absX;
public int absY;
public int heightLevel;[/code]


This can pretty much be simplified into [b]one[/b] field using data encapsulation...


[code=java]public Position playerPosition;[/code]

Ironically, you can find a simple [i]container[/i] class I made for Positions, [url=http://www.moparisthebest.com/smf/index.php/topic,625675.0.html]here[/url].




[anchor=clickme4][u][b]IV. What is an Object/Instance and how it relates to Data Encapsulation[/b][/u][/anchor]

[u]What is an [i]Object[/i]?[/u]

[quote="Clawz fury, post:1, topic:478532"][i]Object[/i] is the superclass of all classes, or in other terms every class extends Object. This is why you can do something like:

[code=java]public Object instanceOfAClass = new RandomClassHere();[/code]

All classes are Objects, meaning an Object can carry an instance of any class.[/quote]

[u]What is an [i]Instance[/i]?[/u]

[quote="Clawz fury, post:1, topic:478532"]Object and instance are the same thing.

[code=java]public PlayerHandler handler;[/code]

You can refer to this as an Object because PlayerHandlers superclass is Object. But if I saw this anywhere I'd probably refer to it as an instance. Eg:

An [i]instance[/i] of the Server class

[code=java]public Server serverInstance = new Server();[/code]

An [i]Object[/i]

[code=java]public Server serverInstance;[/code][/quote]

[u]How it relates to Data Encapsulation[/u]

This relates to Data Encapsulation because as as I said in the beginning

<blockquote>It's pretty much packaging all of your seperated data into one [i]Object[/i]</blockquote>
This means, since our [i]container[/i] class is an [i]Object[/i], we can declare it as a field or parameter. Even as a generic type!

And what does this mean? This means we can write

[code=java]private Position position = new Position(...);[/code]

[code=java]public void movePlayer(Position position) {
     ...
}[/code]

[code=java]public List<Position> coordinates = new ArrayList<Position>(...);[/code] 

and much more :)


[anchor=clickme5][u][b]V. Our very first [i]Container[/i] Class[/b][/u][/anchor]

Lets find another specific example in winterlove where encapsulation should be used... how about [i]items[/i]? What does one item consist of?

An [i]item ID[/i]

And an [i]item amount[/i]

So, create a new class and name it [i]Item[/i]. Inside put

[code=java]/**
 * Holds data for an item
 * 
 * @author lare96
 */
public class Item {

	/**
	 * The item id
	 */
	private int id;

	/**
	 * The amount
	 */
	private int amount;
}[/code]

Now we need the constructor, and the getters n' setters. This setters will help us set the variables in the new instance we create, and they will also help have total control over what is stored in our fields. You'll see.

Add this constructor. This will basically allow us to instantiate the Item class and set the variables

[code=java]        /**
	 * Constructs a new container with the specified data
	 */
	public Item(int id, int amount) {
		this.setId(id);
		this.setAmount(amount);
	}[/code]

Now for the setters... see how we can manage the input data? If someone inputs an id/amount below one, or over the max integer limit, it will change the data to something that won't cause any errors.

[code=java]    /**
     * @param item
     *            the item to set
     */
    public void setId(int id) {
        if (id < 1) {
            this.id = 1;
        } else if (id > Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
            this.id = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        }

        this.id = id;
    }

    /**
     * @param amount
     *            the amount to set
     */
    public void setAmount(int amount) {
        if (amount < 1) {
            this.amount = 1;
        } else if (amount > Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
            this.amount = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        }

        this.amount = amount;
    }[/code]

Now for the getters, so we can retrieve the data!

[code=java]	/**
	 * @return the item
	 */
	public int getId() {
		return id;
	}

	/**
	 * @return the amount
	 */
	public int getAmount() {
		return amount;
	}[/code]

And that's it..! Extremely simple. Your class should now look like:

[code=java]/**
 * Holds data for an item
 * 
 * @author lare96
 */
public class Item {

    /**
     * The item id
     */
    private int id;

    /**
     * The amount
     */
    private int amount;

    /**
     * Constructs a new container with the specified data
     */
    public Item(int id, int amount) {
        this.setId(id);
        this.setAmount(amount);
    }

    /**
     * @return the item
     */
    public int getId() {
        return id;
    }

    /**
     * @param item
     *            the item to set
     */
    public void setId(int id) {
        if (id < 1) {
            this.id = 1;
        } else if (id > Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
            this.id = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        }

        this.id = id;
    }

    /**
     * @return the amount
     */
    public int getAmount() {
        return amount;
    }

    /**
     * @param amount
     *            the amount to set
     */
    public void setAmount(int amount) {
        if (amount < 1) {
            this.amount = 1;
        } else if (amount > Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
            this.amount = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        }

        this.amount = amount;
    }
}[/code]




[anchor=clickme6][u][b]VI. How we can use it[/b][/u][/anchor]

[code=java]private static Item ABYSSAL_WHIP = new Item(4151, 1);
private static Item MAX_GOLD = new Item(995, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

public void giveRares(Player player) {
     player.addItem(ABYSSAL_WHIP.getID(), ABYSSAL_WHIP.getAmount());
     player.addItem(MAX_GOLD.getID(), MAX_GOLD.getAmount());
}[/code]

[code=java]public static List<Item> partyRoomChestItems = new ArrayList<Item>();

public void addItemToChest() {
     partyRoomChestItems.add(new Item(995, 300));
     partyRoomChestItems.add(new Item(4151, 1));
     partyRoomChestItems.add(new Item(556, 30000));
}

public Item getChestItems() {
    for(Item chestItems : partyRoomChestItems) {
         return chestItems;
    }
}

public void addChestItems(Player player) {
     player.addItem(getChestItems().getId(), getChestItems().getAmount());
}[/code]


Horrible examples, but you get the picture. Anything I missed out feel free to point it out.




